Ronbot Control Panel — Cursor Rules (v3.0)These rules apply to the Ronbot Control Panel: a clean, production-grade Electron desktop companion for the Hermes agent (Nous Research). The app’s role is to install the latest official Hermes (if requested) and seed custom personality files, then act as a novice-friendly live dashboard and chat interface. The agent itself owns all configuration, skills, platforms, and customization via natural chat.Core Product VisionThe app is a lightweight installer + companion dashboard, not a heavy controller or wizard system.
Primary interface = in-app chat with Hermes (Home tab).
After installation, the app seeds the user’s custom personality files so the agent immediately behaves as intended.
The agent handles all ongoing configuration (connecting WhatsApp/Discord, adding skills, creating cron jobs, sub-agents, etc.) through chat.
App is read-only for changes: buttons only insert helpful pre-filled prompts into the chat.
Must remain novice-friendly, simple, clean, and suitable for casual users.
Cross-platform: fully functional on macOS, Linux, and Windows (via WSL2). Never assume native Windows support.

Installer RequirementsOn first launch or via Install page: detect if Hermes is already installed (hermes version or binary check).
If not installed or user chooses “Install latest Hermes”, run the official one-line installer from GitHub:bash

curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/main/scripts/install.sh | bash

(This always installs the newest version.)
Use runCommandStream with proper OS detection and WSL2 routing on Windows.
After successful install: auto-start the gateway, then seed the custom personality files (see below).
Show rich progress UI with live streamed output and clear success/failure states.

Personality File Seeding (post-install)Immediately after install, atomically write the following files to ~/.hermes/ (or the equivalent WSL2 path):SOUL.md
PERSONALITY.md
memories/MEMORY.md
memories/USER.md
AGENTS.md (include a short instruction that points the agent to ELECTRON_APP_GUIDE.md for how to interact with the app — modals for QR codes, password/key requests, etc.)

Use safe, managed file writing (read first if exists, only overwrite default Hermes content). Never blindly overwrite user customizations.Architecture — never break these patternsAll OS access goes through window.electronAPI → src/lib/systemAPI/*. Never import child_process, fs, path, os in renderer code.
IPC handlers live in electron/main.cjs. Bridge surface is electron/preload.cjs (CommonJS).
Secrets go through secretsStore (src/lib/systemAPI/secretsStore.ts). Never write secrets to ~/.hermes/.env from the UI. Materialize on demand only.
Long-running commands use runCommandStream + onCommandOutput. Always store the unsubscribe function and call it in cleanup.
State: React contexts only. No Redux, Zustand, Jotai, Recoil.
Routing: HashRouter only (file:// compatible).
Vite base: "./" in vite.config.ts is mandatory.

Hermes-Specific RulesUse only official Hermes CLI commands and the official install script. Never invent custom install methods.
After seeding personality files, the agent is responsible for all further setup (platforms, skills, cron, sub-agents, etc.).
Preserve existing left sidebar + tab structure.
On the Home (chat) tab only: add a collapsible right sidebar showing live agent activity (sub-agents, cron jobs, heartbeat tasks).
Auto-refresh right sidebar every 5 seconds via lightweight polling of official Hermes commands.
Modals for QR codes, images, password/key requests, etc., triggered by special markers in agent responses.
Maintain ~/.hermes/ELECTRON_APP_GUIDE.md so the agent knows how to interact with the app.
Gateway: auto-start on app launch after install. Provide simple dashboard controls (start/stop/restart).

Code Quality & Maintainability (new emphasis)Write clean, readable, efficient TypeScript code. Follow standard professional patterns.
Prefer small, focused functions and components.
Regularly remove unused code, dead imports, and commented-out sections.
Avoid spaghetti code, deep nesting, and duplicated logic.
Keep the codebase minimal — the app is intentionally lightweight.
Use existing contexts (CapabilitiesContext, InstallContext, etc.) as the single source of truth.
Preserve all existing architecture rules (IPC boundary, secretsStore, etc.).
Avoid patches and workarounds.

Stack — do not deviateVite 5 + React 18 + TypeScript 5 + Tailwind 3 + shadcn/ui + framer-motion
Electron 41, packaged with @electron/packager (NOT electron-builder)
Package manager: bun (bun.lockb)
Testing: vitest + @testing
-library/react

Design system — token-driven onlyAll colors are HSL CSS variables in src/index.css. Never use raw hex/rgb.
Use semantic Tailwind tokens and existing glass utilities.
Fonts: Inter (body), JetBrains Mono (code/logs).

SecurityNever echo secrets in logs.
Never write secrets directly to .env from UI.

NeverNever reintroduce heavy wizards for WhatsApp, skills, platforms, etc. The agent now owns these via chat.
Never reintroduce Supabase, Lovable Cloud, or any remote backend.
Never run package managers from renderer — always through runCommand.
Never use electron-builder.
Never assume native Windows support for Hermes — always route through WSL2 on Windows.
Never expose raw CLI output to the user unless in a controlled progress view.

App-specific notesIn-app chat is the primary way users communicate with Hermes.
Ronbot / Hermes naming: use “Hermes” where it improves clarity.
Provider-agnostic: all model/API keys managed via secretsStore.
CapabilitiesContext remains the single source of truth for displayed capabilities.
Preserve cross-platform installer and WSL2 support exactly as built.

